{"name":"Thom","meanings":["Scottish and English: from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)om(me)</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . In Scotland, <i>Thom</i> is also an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Thom</i>, see   McComb  .","German: from the personal name <i>Thom</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . This surname is also found in France.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 譚, see   Tan   1."]},{"name":"Tomson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thompsom","meanings":["Altered form of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Tompson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]}]},{"name":"Maurice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Mauricius</i>, a derivative of <i>Maurus</i> (a byname meaning ‘Moor’, i.e. ‘dark, swarthy’), borne by, among others, an early Byzantine emperor (  <i>c.</i>539–602 ). It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was popular in the Middle English period, but was not widely adopted by the nobility and became rare in the 17th century. Between the mid-19th century and the 1940s, it was moderately popular but has since faded again.  See also  Morris ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maurice Thompson was born in 1530, in Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Thomson, was 30 and his mother, Kathern Hill, was 30. He married Katherine Harvey in 1550, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1560, in Cheshunt, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1530–1560":"1530–1560","1530–1551":"1530–1551","1535–1560":"1535–1560","1555–Female":"1555–Surnud","1575–Male":"1575–Surnud","1560–1620":"1560–1620","1560–1648":"1560–1648","1500–1568":"1500–1568","1500–1565":"1500–1565","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1568":"1568","1535":"1535","1500":"1500","1555":"1555","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1575":"1575","1530":"1530","1551":"1551","Abt. 1560":"umbe